{{Infobox settlement |official_name = Bellefonte, Alabama |settlement_type = [[Ghost town]] |image_skyline = Bellfonte, Alabama- The Chimney of the Local Inn.JPG |imagesize = |image_caption = The chimney of the local inn in foreground, with [[Bellefonte Nuclear Generating Station]] in the background |image_seal = |image_map = |mapsize = |map_caption = |pushpin_map = Alabama#USA |pushpin_label = Bellefonte |pushpin_label_position = left |pushpin_map_caption = |subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]] |subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]] |subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Alabama|County]] |subdivision_name = United States |subdivision_name1 = [[Alabama]] |subdivision_name2 = [[Jackson County, Alabama|Jackson]] |government_type = |leader_title = |leader_name = |established_date = |area_magnitude = |area_total_km2 = |area_total_sq_mi = |area_land_km2 = |area_land_sq_mi = |area_water_km2 = |area_water_sq_mi = |elevation_ft = 745 |elevation_m = 227 |population_as_of = |population_footnotes = |population_total = |population_metro = |population_density_km2 = |population_density_sq_mi = |timezone = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]] |utc_offset = -6 |coordinates = {{coord|34|42|40|N|85|56|43|W|region:US-AL|display=inline,title}} |timezone_DST = CDT |utc_offset_DST = -5 |postal_code_type = [[ZIP code]] |postal_code = 35752 |area_code = [[Area code 256|256]] |blank_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID |blank_info = 0113878 |footnotes = |website = }} '''Bellefonte''' is a [[ghost town]] in [[Jackson County, Alabama|Jackson County]], [[Alabama]], United States,<ref>{{gnis|113878}}</ref> near the site of the [[Bellefonte Nuclear Generating Station]]. It is located roughly two miles southeast of [[Hollywood, Alabama]].
==Demographics== Bellefonte was listed on the 1860 and 1870 U.S. Census rolls. In 1860, it was the most populous (and only) incorporated community in Jackson County with 181 persons (of whom 173 were White, and 8 were "Free Colored"; no slaves were recorded.)<ref>[http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1860a-04.pdf]</ref>
{{US Census population |1860= 181 |1870= 72 |align-fn=center |footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |title=U.S. Decennial Census |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=June 6, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YSasqtfX?url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |archivedate=May 12, 2015 |df= }}</ref> }}
==History== Bellefonte was settled in the early 19th century and incorporated on December 15, 1821,<ref name="alabama-law-1823-lxiii">A Digest of the Laws of the State of Alabama: Containing The Statutes and Resolutions in Force at the end of the General Assembly in January, 1823. Published by Ginn & Curtis, J. & J. Harper, Printers, New-York, 1828. Title 62. Chapter LXIII. Page 839. [https://books.google.com/books?id=JvtKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA839 "An Act to Incorporate the Town of Belle-Fonte, in the County of Jackson.—Passed December 15, 1821." (Google Books)]</ref> when it had nearly 200 residents. Its name was a subjective description consisting of the French words "belle", meaning "beautiful," and "fonte", meaning "fount." It was the [[Jackson County, Alabama|Jackson County]] [[county seat|seat]] from 1821 to 1868, when it was relocated to [[Scottsboro, Alabama|Scottsboro]].
During the 1820s, a courthouse and church were constructed. A post office was established in 1830. By 1844, the population had grown to 400. The town suffered severe damage during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. The post office was closed in 1859.
The relocation of the county seat in 1868 drew off business from town. This town rapidly lost population, dropping off the census rolls by 1880. The town was abandoned by the 1920s. All that remains of Bellefonte today are the cemetery, the chimney of the local [[Public house#Inns|inn]], and piles of scattered bricks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dream Has Gone: Civil War, Rejection of Railroad Led to Bellefonte's Demise|work=Huntsville Times|first=Jeff |last=Tryon|date=July 6, 1986}}</ref><ref>Foscue, Virginia. ''Place Names in Alabama''. University: U of Alabama Press, 1989.</ref>
