'''Radyo an Gernewegva''' (abbreviated as RanG; meaning in English 'radio of the Cornish-speaking area') is a radio service broadcasting through the medium of the [[Cornish language]] both online, via [[podcast]], and on several [[community radio]] stations in [[Cornwall]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is a [[not-for-profit organisation]], and receives some funding through the [[Cornish Language Partnership]]. It is produced by [[KernowPods]].<ref name="Celtic Media Festival: Radio Station of the Year">{{cite web|title=Celtic Media Festival: Radio Station of the Year|url=http://www.celticmediafestival.co.uk/winner/409|publisher=Celtic Media Festival|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>
==History== The service began in 2007 as 'Nowodhow an Seythun' (News of the Week). This was a short 4 minute podcast, distributed each week through a collection of Cornish cultural websites. This service was increased to half an hour each week in 2008, and adopted the new name "Radyo an Gernewegva". The format changed at this point to become a magazine programme, incorporating music, discussion and news. In 2010, Radyo an Gernewegva incorporated the original 'Nowodhow an Seythun' back into the service. In 2013 it was shortlisted for Radio Station of the Year at the [[Celtic Media Festival]].<ref name="Celtic Media Festival: Radio Station of the Year"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesscornwall.co.uk/news-by-industry/creative-industries-in-cornwall/kernowpods-up-for-award-123 |title=Cornish language podcast shortlisted for Celtic Media Festival |publisher=Business Cornwall |date=2013-02-14 |accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref> In that same year a [[crowdfunding]] campaign was launched to raise funds for a new website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiscornwall.co.uk/Cornish-language-station-seeks-pound-5k/story-19755002-detail/story.html#axzz2ifZ9cye8 |title=Cornish language station seeks £5k in crowdfunding for website &#124; West Briton |publisher=Thisiscornwall.co.uk |date=2013-09-05 |accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesscornwall.co.uk/latest-news/crowd-funding-for-new-website-123 |title=Cornish language podcast turns to crowd funding for new website |publisher=Business Cornwall |date=2013-08-09 |accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref> The campaign was successful, raising over £5,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magakernow.org.uk/default.aspx?page=855 |accessdate=October 24, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192712/http://www.magakernow.org.uk/default.aspx?page=855 |archivedate=October 29, 2013 }}</ref> Listening to Radyo an Gernewegva is recommended as an aid to learning the [[Cornish language]] by the ''Say Something in Cornish'' course.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://site.saysomethingin.com/communities/cornish-for-english-speakers/courses/course-1-kwen |title=SaySomethingIn |publisher=Site.saysomethingin.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-09}}</ref> It attracts more than 500 listeners every week.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}
In 2014 the service began to be broadcast by several [[community radio]] stations in Cornwall. [[Radio St Austell Bay]] broadcasts it every Sunday, at midday, [[Source fm]] ([[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] and [[Penryn, Cornwall|Penryn]]) broadcasts the same programme every Tuesday at 1pm,{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} The Hub Radio [[Roseland, Cornwall]] broadcasts it every Saturday at 6am and [[Coast FM (West Cornwall)|Coast FM]] [[Penwith, Cornwall]] plays the programme 3 times a week.
==Presenters== Matthew Clarke is the main presenter<ref name="Celtic Media Festival: Radio Station of the Year"/> and [[James Hawken]], [[Tim Saunders]] and [[Nicholas Williams]] all provide regular content.
